`,Ut(t.p,{children:"TimeFlow feeds two brain MRI scans — taken at different ages — into a time-conditioned neural network. The network learns to warp the earlier scan into any requested future state, producing both a predicted brain image and the underlying spatial deformation. Crucially, only two visits are needed: no dense time series, no intermediate scans."}),`
`,Ut(t.p,{children:["A novel ",Ut(t.strong,{children:"bidirectional consistency loss"})," (specifically consisting of ",Ut(t.strong,{children:"interpolation and extrapolation consistency losses"}),') ensures predictions are coherent across time: forward and backward deformations must agree, so the model never "cheats" with discontinuous jumps. This removes the usual need for explicit smoothness penalties while enforcing temporal stability.']}),`
